AUDIO: 'and then create that model. Now, it\'s not going&nbsp; to be perfect straight away. So, you know,&nbsp;&nbsp; if you put it through a generator and it comes out&nbsp; of a bit of a wonky hand or something like that,&nbsp;&nbsp; that\'s just AI. The probability of it being&nbsp; perfect is obviously a lot lower. But,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[19:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'um, you can always do a bit of post-production,&nbsp; bit of editing, and just improve that overall. So,&nbsp;&nbsp; don\'t get emotionally attached to your model. That&nbsp; is one very, very important thing that you guys&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[19:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'need to understand. Now, a lot of people when they&nbsp; start chatting or doing any of this kind of jazz,&nbsp;&nbsp; they get very attached to the model and they end&nbsp; up talking to the customers and actually really&nbsp;&nbsp; enjoying this conversation and then they never&nbsp; end up scaling. Similar with your model. You don\'t&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[19:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'want to get attached to that model because if the&nbsp; quality isn\'t good enough, then you may have to&nbsp;&nbsp; restart. So, obviously, if the model\'s at like 500&nbsp; count Instagram, yeah, get attached to that model.&nbsp;&nbsp; make sure they\'re getting the correct care. But&nbsp; at the start, you don\'t want to be obsessed with&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[20:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'creating one model that\'s maybe like very low&nbsp; quality and then getting stuck on just trying&nbsp;&nbsp; to make content for this lowquality model. You&nbsp; want to just dispose of whatever images that&nbsp;&nbsp; you get until you get a very high quality model&nbsp; which you can then pursue. Um so yeah, make sure&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[20:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you look into that. Three hours on one image. Now,&nbsp; a lot of people do this um and it is quite quite&nbsp;&nbsp; annoying. So, they find a reference image online,&nbsp; maybe one that Cole brought up earlier, you know,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[20:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'where she was sitting there in a bikini with a&nbsp; glass. People try to replicate that and they try&nbsp;&nbsp; to replicate it to kind of like a pinpoint. They&nbsp; spend hours just trying to generate the same image&nbsp;&nbsp; over and over again and it\'s not working. Don\'t do&nbsp; this. Image images that you make, you\'re going to&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[20:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'be making for marketing. They\'re going to be used&nbsp; most likely once or twice and then disposed of.&nbsp;&nbsp; So making more images slightly quicker is always&nbsp; going to be favored because marketing is obviously&nbsp;&nbsp; the most important thing. And as you know speed&nbsp; is very very important. So don\'t get fixated on&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[21:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one image for 3 4 hours. That\'s stupid. Try&nbsp; to get images out. If they\'re not perfect,&nbsp;&nbsp; you know, do a bit of post-production or discard&nbsp; the image. Don\'t sit there for half hour trying&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[21:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to fix it trying to get the exact content you&nbsp; want. You know, just carry on basically. But&nbsp;&nbsp; um let\'s look at creating faces. So when you do&nbsp; create a face, there\'s obviously multiple options&nbsp;&nbsp; depending on your niche, but most of the time,&nbsp; as Cole mentioned, that kind of youth, youthful,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[21:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'innocent, or friendly kind of look is normally&nbsp; what customers prefer. Having it kind of useful,&nbsp;&nbsp; once again, the older guys that most likely&nbsp; are going to buy this content are going to&nbsp;&nbsp; want to be able to, let\'s say, tell the models&nbsp; things and communicate with the models to kind&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[21:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of show them the world as kind of most BS want to&nbsp; do. Um, so that youthful look is normally quite&nbsp;&nbsp; good and obviously desired by most older guys or&nbsp; of customers for some weird reason, but that\'s&nbsp;&nbsp; true. And also, if there is only like young lads&nbsp; that are on these platforms, they seem to be able&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[22:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to relate with these c these models a lot better.&nbsp; Innocent and friendly. This is just mainly for the&nbsp;&nbsp; approachability of the model, which is very good.&nbsp; So having a friendly looking face is obviously&nbsp;&nbsp; meaning that the person\'s most likely going&nbsp; to talk to the model and start a conversation&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[22:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because you want them to start a conversation.&nbsp; You don\'t want to have like a weird, you know,&nbsp;&nbsp; pirate looking fella cuz no one\'s going to chat&nbsp; to it. So you want to make a friendly face so they&nbsp;&nbsp; start conversation cuz that is where you\'re going&nbsp; to make the money in the chats. Upselling people&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[22:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on images in the DMs on fan view is where you&nbsp; make the money. So, you want that kind of friendly&nbsp;&nbsp; uh approachable look. Now, creating full body&nbsp; content. Now, this is uh the slightly harder part.&nbsp;&nbsp; The face is normally not too hard. If you can get&nbsp; the face nailed, AI is pretty good with that. But&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[23:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'keeping a consistent body is quite hard. So, this&nbsp; is where people use consistent prompts to be able&nbsp;&nbsp; to generate the same thing. So if you did have&nbsp; let\'s say you know 100 word prompts maybe 15 or 20&nbsp;&nbsp; of them um words are specific to to the body and&nbsp; will be reused throughout your generators which&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[23:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
