[23:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'um yeah so what\'s best for a lura? Now luras are&nbsp; very uh let\'s say controversial. Some people use&nbsp;&nbsp; massive data set of like 100 images and they train&nbsp; it very very well and it\'s a very good lura. Some&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[23:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'people do the opposite. They create loras from&nbsp; about five images and then have a very consistent&nbsp;&nbsp; face and then go build more content to then build&nbsp; a better and stronger lura. So it depends on what&nbsp;&nbsp; your method you\'re doing. But the one we normally&nbsp; teach in the course, which is what most people end&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[24:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'end up doing, is around 20 images. Now, this&nbsp; is going to be five close-up facial images,&nbsp;&nbsp; so the AI knows how much detail to put the face in&nbsp; from all different positions. Five bone selfie POV&nbsp;&nbsp; images. And the reason you do that is because&nbsp; you then give a bit of diversity to the Laura.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[24:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If you just use the same, you know, close-up&nbsp; mug shots, you\'re only going to get close-up&nbsp;&nbsp; mug shots. If you got selfies, bit diverse, you&nbsp; know, half body, full body, then the Laura is&nbsp;&nbsp; going to be a bit more diverse. So you can&nbsp; then create more images and expand on that,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[24:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which is obviously exactly what you want to&nbsp; do. Facial expressions are quite important as&nbsp;&nbsp; well. So do try vary the facial expressions.&nbsp; The amount of times people say, "Oh, that\'s&nbsp;&nbsp; an AI model because it looks the same in all the&nbsp; pictures," is because of the facial expressions.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[24:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So make sure some of them are smiling, you&nbsp; know, frowning, laughing. You can do this on&nbsp;&nbsp; platforms like Open Art where you can literally&nbsp; just change the face for free, give it a smile,&nbsp;&nbsp; you know, whatever. But open art is a way that you&nbsp; can obviously manipulate facial expressions. Um,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[25:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'half body images obviously very important as well&nbsp; because you want to show the background and also&nbsp;&nbsp; the structure of the model. And then obviously&nbsp; full body images, same same detail, you know,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[25:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
